<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>SINGLE REDUCTION, TANDEM AXLES: SPICER J400-S, W460-S - INSTALL - PINION POSITION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="install" graphiccount="7">
        <title>PINION POSITION</title>
        <para>Ring gears and pinions are supplied in matched sets only. Matching numbers on both the pinion and ring
            gear are etched for verification. If a new gear set is being used, verify the numbers of each pinion and
            ring gear before proceeding with assembly (refer to
            <hotlnk document="s14004_HL1400403.xml" xrefid="hl1400403">IDENTIFICATION, GEAR SET</hotlnk>
            for location of numbers.)
        </para>
        <para>Pinion position is based on nominal mounting distance measured from the centerline of the ring gear to the
            button end of the pinion (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f14004b9">Figure 119</hotlnk>). This dimension is controlled by selectively shimming between
            the pinion cage assembly and the carrier housing. The nominal dimension for the J Model carriers is 3.7695
            inches (95.7453 mm). The nominal dimension for the W Model carriers is 4.2845 inches (108.826 mm).
        </para>
        <figure id="f14004b9" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g14004b9" filename="../figg14/G14004B9.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 118. Measure Nominal Mounting Distance</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Be sure mounting surfaces are free of burrs and dirt prior to assembly as they will affect pinion
                    position.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To establish the correct nominal dimension by using a pinion setting gauge, install pinion
                gear and cage assembly into the carrier housing without shims. Tighten pinion cage bolts to 115 to 135
                ft-lbs. (156 to 183 Nm) on all forward carriers and the J Model rear carriers. The W Model rear carriers
                require 160 to 185 ft-lbs. (217 to 251 Nm) torque. Failure to tighten properly may result in incorrect
                gear adjustment.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Attach the step plate clamp assembly to the carrier mounting flange. Locate step plate clamp
                screw over center of pinion gear. Install step plate under clamp screw and tighten to hold step plate
                securely in position (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f14004c0">Figure 120</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f14004c0" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g14004c0" filename="../figg14/G14004C0.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 119. Attach Step Plate Clamp Assembly to Carrier Mounting Flange</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Be sure lugs on bottom of step plate straddle the bearing staking indentations on end of
                        pinion, or false reading may occur. Also, make sure differential side bearing bores are clean
                        and free of nicks.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove any burrs and wipe clean differential bearing bore l.D.s. Turn micrometer 90 degrees
                to step plate. Install assembled pinion setting gauge into bearing bores of carrier housing until fully
                seated. Adjust micrometer so it is directly over end of step plate. Run the micrometer thimble down to
                measure the distance between the center of the ring gear and the step plate (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f14004c1">Figure 121</hotlnk>).
                <emph type="bold">Make a note of this dimension</emph>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f14004c1" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g14004c1" filename="../figg14/G14004C1.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 120. Measure Distance Between Center of Ring Gear and Step Plate</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Because the step plate must be taken into consideration, the thickness of the step
                    plate [.400 inch (10.16 mm)] needs to be added to the measured value for the correct micrometer
                    distance.
                </emph>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">On the machined end of each pinion gear is etched either a plus (+) number, a minus (-)
                number or a zero (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f14004c2">Figure 122</hotlnk>). This number represents the amount in thousandths of an
                inch (.001) to be added (+) or subtracted (-) from the nominal dimension for the best running position
                for that particular gear set.
            </para>
            <figure id="f14004c2" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g14004c2" filename="../figg14/G14004C2.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 121. Number Etched on Machined End of Each Pinion Gear</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>EXAMPLE: If pinion is etched +3, the required mounting distance is more than nominal by .003 in. (.076
                mm). This means the pinion would require .003 in. (.076 mm) thicker shim between pinion bearing cage
                assembly and carrier housing than a pinion etched with "0".
            </para>
            <para>If the pinion is marked -3, the shim required between pinion bearing cage assembly and carrier housing
                would be .003 in. (.076 mm) thinner than if pinion was etched "0".
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The following two examples illustrate how proper running position is achieved by computing
                dimensions you have obtained.
            </para>
